    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>G31.41+0.31 is a well studied hot molecular core (HMC) for which signs of rotation and infall have been found. Recently, we reconstructed the 3-D velocities of the water masers in the core via multi-epoch VLBI observations, revealing a collimated bipolar jet powered by an unresolved centimeter source. The jet dynamical timescale is only 1300 yr; this is a reliable estimate of the true age of the jet and not a lower limit, because the jet is still fully embedded inside the core, and no extended components of it are missed. All these findings suggest that we deal with a deeply embedded high-mass (proto)star undergoing accretion and powering the youngest jet ever detected from this type of objects. We propose to determine the detailed jet structure by means of 0.2" resolution imaging of the SiO(8-7) line, which we already mapped with the SMA at lower angular resolution (0.8") and sensitivity. The SMA data indicate that the SiO emission peaks along the border of the H2O maser jet, thus lending support to the present proposal. The outcome of the ALMA observations will help addressing issues like the jet acceleration mechanism and the possible existence of jet rotation and/or precession.</prp:abstract>
